# Context

Headline result from Hwangbo et al. and Zhu et al.: neural actuator models achieve sub-1 Nm RMSE on both torque-controlled AND position-controlled actuators of comparable scale. Our v1 GRU achieves 0.37 Nm on tStep but 67.25 Nm on PLC — two orders of magnitude gap within the same model. This is not replicated in the literature. The gap must trace to one of: (1) mixed-profile training dilutes each profile's fit, (2) feature set differences (we include torEst/accelAct which Hwangbo omitted), (3) excitation range differences, (4) control topology differences, or (5) window/rate mismatches.

This prompt isolates cause (1) specifically: does training one model per profile type recover literature-level RMSE on each?

# Task

Retrain MLP and GRU from scratch, 4 times each, on only the training data of one profile type:

- model_PLC: trained on PLC training data only
- model_PMS: trained on PMS training data only
- model_TMS: trained on TMS training data only
- model_tStep: trained on tStep training data only

Same hyperparameters as v1. Same seeds. Same SEQ_LEN=30. Same feature set. Checkpoints in `checkpoints/per_profile/{profile}_{arch}.pt`.

For each of the 8 models, evaluate on:
- its own profile's held-out test samples (primary metric)
- every other profile's held-out test samples (to quantify generalization loss)

