# Interpretation block

- "Per-profile training closes the gap": if per-profile PLC GRU achieves RMSE < 5 Nm. Means cause (1) (dilution from mixed training) is dominant. Thesis implication: literature-replication requires per-profile models, and the v1 "universal model" framing was the problem.
- "Per-profile partially closes the gap": if per-profile PLC GRU achieves 5-30 Nm. Dilution is real but not the full story; causes (2)-(5) contribute.
- "Per-profile does not close the gap": if per-profile PLC GRU RMSE stays > 30 Nm. Means the PLC data itself is harder to fit than the literature benchmarks suggest, regardless of training-set composition. Pivot to causes (2)-(5).

Cross-profile matrix diagnostic: examine whether diagonal < off-diagonal universally. If the PLC-trained model has low PLC RMSE but catastrophic RMSE on tStep test data, it means PLC and tStep live in genuinely different feature distributions that cannot be jointly modeled without sacrificing one. This is a structural finding.

Training dynamics diagnostic: examine whether PLC specifically shows high val/train ratio or plateaued val loss. If PLC val/train ratio >> other profiles', PLC training is unstable (overfits or underfits differently) and may need profile-specific hyperparameters.

# Requirements

- Each per-profile model gets the same train/val/test split structure (70/15/15 chronological per file) but applied only within that profile's files.
- Re-fit scaler per profile — the scaling statistics are profile-dependent.
- Log training curves for all 8 runs. Identical plotting style to prior sweeps so comparisons are direct.
- v1 baseline numbers in the primary table must come from evaluating v1 on the per-profile test subsets. If v1 was evaluated on combined test set only, run this evaluation now using the v1 checkpoint — no retraining needed for baseline.

# Deliverables

1. `experiments/outputs/per_profile_training.md` with all three tables, interpretation, and training-dynamics summary.
